{{Year box}}
Events from the year '''2002 in the [[European Union]]'''.
==Incumbents== * '''[[President of the European Commission|Commission President]]''' — [[Romano Prodi]] * '''[[Presidency of the Council of the European Union|Council Presidency]]''' — [[Spain]] (January–June), [[Denmark]] (July–December) * '''[[President of the European Parliament|Parliament President]]''' — [[Nicole Fontaine]] (until 15 January), [[Pat Cox]] * '''[[High Representative for Common Foreign and Security Policy|High Representative]]''' — [[Javier Solana]]
==Events== * 1 January - **[[Spain]] takes over the [[Presidency of the European Union]]. **[[Euro]] notes and coins issued are in [[Austria]], [[Belgium]], [[France]], [[Finland]], [[Germany]], [[Greece]], [[Ireland]], [[Italy]], [[Luxembourg]], the [[Netherlands]], [[Portugal]] and Spain.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/business/1736296.stm|title=Euro becomes a reality|work=BBC News|publisher=BBC|date=31 December 2001|accessdate=22 November 2013}}</ref> * 15 January - Irish [[Member of the European Parliament|MEP]] [[Pat Cox]] is elected President of the European Parliament.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.irishtimes.com/news/cox-salutes-and-thanks-meps-after-election-victory-1.1046761|title=Cox 'salutes and thanks' MEPs after election victory|newspaper=The Irish Times|publisher=The Irish Times Limited|date=16 January 2002|accessdate=6 December 2013}}{{paywall}}</ref> * 28 February - The Euro becomes the sole legal tender in all 12 [[Eurozone]] countries.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/business/1845045.stm|title=Euro changeover complete|work=BBC News|publisher=BBC|date=28 February 2002|accessdate=22 November 2013}}</ref> * 31 May - All 15 member nations of the European Union ratify the [[Kyoto Protocol]], committing to an 8% cut in [[carbon dioxide]] emissions between 2008 and 2012 compared to 1990 levels.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://usatoday30.usatoday.com/news/healthscience/science/climate/2002-05-31-kyoto.htm|title=European Union ratifies Kyoto treaty|website=USA Today|publisher=Gannett Company|date=31 May 2002|accessdate=22 November 2013}}</ref> * 1 July - [[Denmark]] takes over the [[Presidency of the European Union]]. * 19 October - In a second referendum, the electorate of Ireland votes in favour of ratifying the [[Treaty of Nice]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/worldnews/europe/ireland/1410856/Ireland-says-yes-to-Nice-treaty.html|title=Ireland says yes to Nice treaty|newspaper=The Telegraph|publisher=Telegraph Media Group|first=Thomas|last=Harding|date=21 October 2002|accessdate=23 November 2013}}</ref>
