[[Image:Cotonoucathedral.jpg|thumb|The [[Cotonou Cathedral|cathedral of Notre Dame des Apôtres]] in [[Cotonou]]]]
'''Christians in Benin''' constitute approximately 42.8 percent (~3,762,904) of the country's population (8,791,832<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cia.gov/library/publications/the-world-factbook/geos/bn.html |title=The World Factbook |publisher=Cia.gov |date= |accessdate=2013-10-21}}</ref> - 2009 est.)

According to the 2002 census, 27.1 percent of the population of Benin is [[Roman Catholic]], 5 percent [[Celestial Christian]], 3.2 percent [[Methodist]], 7.5 percent other [[Christianity|Christian]] groups<ref name=report>[https://www.state.gov/g/drl/rls/irf/2007/90082.htm International Religious Freedom Report 2007: Benin]. United States [[Bureau of Democracy, Human Rights and Labor]] (September 14, 2007). ''This article incorporates text from this source, which is in the [[public domain]].''</ref> ([[Baptists]], [[Assemblies of God]], [[Pentecostals]], [[Seventh-day Adventists]], [[the Church of Jesus Christ of Latter-day Saints]] (Mormons), [[Jehovah's Witnesses]], [[Rosicrucians]], the [[Unification Church]]).

[[Image:Benin - batism ceremony in Cotonou.jpg|thumb|Baptism ceremony of the [[Celestial Church of Christ]] in [[Cotonou]]]]
[[Christianity]] first reached Benin in 1680, gaining more permanent footing in the 19th century. [[England|English]] [[Methodists]] arrived in 1843, operating amongst the coastal [[Gun (African tribe)|Gun]] people.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sim.org/index.php/country/BJ |title=Country Profile: Benin |publisher=Sim.org |date= |accessdate=2013-10-21}}</ref>

== Roman Catholicism ==
{{Main|Roman Catholicism in Benin}}
The Catholic hierarchy in Benin consists of the [[Archdiocese of Cotonou]] (including the Dioceses of [[Roman Catholic Diocese of Abomey|Abomey]], [[Roman Catholic Diocese of Dassa-Zoumé|Dassa-Zoumé]], [[Roman Catholic Diocese of Lokossa|Lokossa]], [[Roman Catholic Diocese of Porto Novo|Porto Novo]]) and the [[Archdiocese of Parakou|Parakou]] (including the Dioceses of [[Roman Catholic Diocese of Djougou|Djougou]], [[Roman Catholic Diocese of Kandi|Kandi]], [[Roman Catholic Diocese of Natitingou|Natitingou]], and [[Roman Catholic Diocese of N'Dali|N'Dali]]). 

In 2011 it was reported that in Benin there were 440 [[priest]]s and 900 men and women in religious orders.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Houngnikpo |first1=Mathurin C. |last2=Decalo |first2=Samuel |date=2013 |title=Historical Dictionary of Benin |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=0yGPTsRubWEC&pg=PA303 |publisher=Rowman & Littlefield |page=94 |isbn=0810871718 |access-date=28 July 2015}}</ref>

Many nominal Christians also practice traditional local religious beliefs.<ref name=report/>
{{Christianity by country}}

