{{refimprove|date=August 2011}} {{multiple image | align = right | image1 = LocationSwaziland.svg | width1 = 220 | caption1 = <center>Location of [[Swaziland]]</center> | image2 = BiltongUKDried.jpg | width2 = 200 | caption2 = <center>Homemade beef [[biltong]], a type of [[Curing (food preservation)|cured meat]] that originated in South Africa</center> }}
The '''cuisine of [[Swaziland]]''' is largely determined by the [[season]]s and the [[Geography of Swaziland|geographical region]]. [[Staple food]]s in Swaziland include [[sorghum]] and [[maize]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.up.ac.za/saafecs/vol28/kgaphola.pdf|title=Food habits of rural Swazi households}}</ref> often served with [[goat meat]], a very popular livestock there.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.journeys2africa.com/j2a/travelguides/swaziland/tg-Swazi-Food.cfm |title=Swaziland Food and Drink |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080919172458/http://www.journeys2africa.com/j2a/travelguides/swaziland/tg-Swazi-Food.cfm |archivedate=2008-09-19 |df= }}</ref> The farming industry mainly depends on [[sugar cane]], [[tobacco]], [[rice]], [[maize|corn]], [[peanut]]s, and the exportation of goat meat and beef. Many Swazis are [[Subsistence farming|subsistence farmers]] who supplement their diet with food bought from markets.
Freshwater produce and imports from coastal nations are also part of the cuisine of Swaziland .<ref name="ref1">[http://www.iexplore.com/dmap/Swaziland/Dining "Swaziland Food and Dining"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20091012192711/http://www.iexplore.com/dmap/Swaziland/Dining |date=2009-10-12 }}. iExplore (website). Accessed May 2010.</ref> Some local markets have food stalls with traditional Swazi meat stew, maize meal and seasonal roasted [[corn on the cob]].<ref name="ref1"/>
==Traditional foods== {{multiple image | align = right | image1 = Ab food 06.jpg | width1 = 214 | caption1 = <center>[[Maize]]</center> | image2 = Pumpkins.jpg | width2 = 220 | caption2 = <center>[[Pumpkin]]s</center> }} {{multiple image | align = right | image1 = Sorghum.jpg | width1 = 243 | caption1 = <center>[[Sorghum]]</center> | image2 = Phaseolus Beans.jpg | width2 = 220 | caption2 = <center>Various types of [[beans]]</center> }}
;Sishwala: Thick [[porridge]] normally served with [[meat]] or [[vegetable]]s ;Incwancwa: Sour porridge made of fermented cornmeal ;Sitfubi: Fresh [[milk]] cooked and mixed with cornmeal ;Siphuphe setindlubu: Thick porridge made of mashed ground nuts ;Emasi etinkhobe temmbila: Ground [[Maize|corn]] mixed with [[sour milk]] ;Emasi emabele: Ground [[sorghum]] mixed with sour milk ;Sidvudvu: Porridge made of [[pumpkin]] mixed with cornmeal ;Umncweba: Dried uncooked meat ([[biltong]]) ;Siphuphe semabhontjisi: Thick porridge made of mashed [[bean]]s ;Tinkhobe: Boiled whole maize ;Umbidvo wetintsanga: Cooked pumpkin tops (leaves) mixed with ground [[Nut (fruit)|nut]]s ;Emahewu: meal drink made from fermented thin porridge ;Umcombotsi : Traditional brewed [[beer]] in Siswati is called 'Tjwala'
