[[File:Bronzeageirishhorns.png|thumb|Bronze Age horns in the Irish Museum. The largest in this image is {{convert|7+1/2|ft}} long, with the second largest at {{convert|6|ft}}.]]
The '''dord''' is a bronze horn native to Ireland, with excavated examples dating back as far as 1000 BC, during the [[Bronze Age]]. 104 original dords are known to exist, although replicas have been built since the late 20th century.<ref>[http://larkinthemorning.com/product.asp?pn=HOR053&Irish+Bronze+Age+Horns=&bhcd2=1243462535]{{dead link|date=December 2016 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}{{Failed verification|date=August 2016}}</ref><!--Lark in the Morning site does not even mention the instrument.-->

Though the musical tradition of the dord has been lost, modern performers such as [[Rolf Harris]] and [[Alan Dargin]] believe it was played in a manner similar to the [[didgeridoo]] and apply that technique (including [[circular breathing]] and shifts in [[timbre]]) accordingly for modern fusion music.  The Irish musician [[Simon O'Dwyer]] attempts to recreate historically accurate dord.<ref>Schellberg, Dirk (1994). ''[https://books.google.com/books?id=hnOOqh6BdYIC&pg=PA46 Didgeridoo: ritual origins and playing techniques]'', p.46. Binkey Kok. {{ISBN|90-74597-13-0}}.</ref>

==See also==
*[[Carnyx]], another type of Celtic trumpet which has been revived

